Introduction


The data we are analyzing is in regards to pet ownership statistics in the United States. The data includes averages of cats and dogs within state households as well as pet owners devotion to their pets, whether the owners are willing to stay at a job they dislike for their pets, and whether the owners were willing to spend $4k to save their pets.

As we go through the nature of the data, we can clearly see the dimensions of the data being 49 observations against 9 variables. These variables are the State, Total Household percentage, Dogs Percentage, Average Number of Dogs, Cats percentage, Average Number of cats, Dogs devotion score, Staying at a job they disliked for dog percentage and Would you spend 4k to save a dog percentage. The structure of the data tells us that the State is the only variable classified as a character; while the others are numeric.

The State variable refers to which U.S. state the other variables are applicable to, the Total Household Percentage variable refers to the percent of households that own a pet. The Dogs and Cats Percentages variables refer to the percentage of households that have dogs or cats. The Number of Dogs and Cats variables refer to the number of dogs or cats per household. The Dog Devotion score refers to how devoted dog owners are to their dogs on the basis of living on a tighter budget to afford their dogs living expenses, how likely they are to move to from an apartment to a house so that their dog can have a yard, and how likely they were to leave a job they liked because another company offered an at home position where they could be with their dog. The variable Staying at a Job They Disliked for Dog Percentage refers to if owners were willing to stay at a job they disliked because it allowed them to work from home or had a dog-friendly office. And finally, the variable Would You spend 4k to Save a Dog Percentage refers to whether dog owners would spend $4,000 or more out-of-pocket on life-saving medical care for their dogs.

2. Boxplots comparing dog versus cat ownership in households

Analysis of both the percentages of cats and dogs and the relationship between using a scatter plot to see the distribution. 

ggplot(pet_data, aes(x=dogsPerc))+ geom_boxplot()

ggplot(pet_data, aes(x=catsPerc))+ geom_boxplot()


In both graphs we can see the distribution of higher percentages in the Dogs Percentages data; while the lower percentages are given to the Cats. The median for dogs would be just below 40; while for cats the median would be just above 25. This median interpretation means that the distribution of dogs percentages is higher than cats. This tells us the strong preference of people for owning dogs.

3. Comparing dog devotion scores versus staying at a job they disliked and spending 4K to save their dog percentages

ggplot(pet_data, aes(x = dogDevScore, y = jobDislikePerc))+
  geom_point(color="salmon") +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", col="lightblue", se=FALSE ,size=1)+ #lm = linear regression
  labs(title = "Percent of Dog Owners who would stay at a job they dislike according to Dog Devotion Score", x = "Dog Devotion Score", y = "jobDislike") +
  theme_dark()

There was no clear correlation for the willingness to stay at a disliked job for each state and the dog devotion score. Since there was no correlation, this simply means there was no clear trend to indicate that a higher likelihood of staying at a disliked job because of the dog would be matched by a higher dog devotion score.

ggplot(pet_data, aes(x = dogDevScore, y = spend4kPerc))+
  geom_point(color="salmon") +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", col="lightblue", se=FALSE ,size=1)+ #lm = linear regression
  labs(title = "Percent of Dog Owners who would spend 4k to save dog compared to Dog Devotion Score", x = "Dog Devotion Score", y = "% Dog Owner Willing to Spend 4k") +
  theme_dark()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'


There was no clear correlation for the dog devotion score or the percent for each state of people willing to spend 4k to save their dog. Since there was no correlation, this simply means there was no clear trend to indicate that a higher likelihood of spending 4k on their dog would be matched by a higher dog devotion score.

After analyzing the data through different statistical tools; we can conclude that there is no correlation between the willingness of someone to spend 4K on their pet and the devotion shown. The results help us understand that despite having a huge appreciation for pets; most people are not willing to spend a great amount of their money. In terms of the devotion to pets and staying in a job you dont like, there is also no correlation between the variables. We can interpret that devotion to a pet is not a factor that affects the willingness of a person to stay working in a job they dont like. In both cases devotion appears not to affect the decisions of the owners of either quitting their job or the decision of spending more of their budget on the pets they have.

4. Comparing spacial correlation with areas where pet owners were willing to spend $4k to save their dog.

We also created a heat map to see if there is any spatial correlation in states and areas where pet owners were willing to spend $4k to save their dog. For this section we pulled from another dataset to get the median household income per state. This was found here: https://worldpopulationreview.com/state-rankings/median-household-income-by-state

# Loading in the income into med_income
med_income <- read.csv(here("DATA","median-household-income-by-state-[updated-august-2023].csv"))
str(med_income)
## 'data.frame':    51 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ state                    : chr  "Maryland" "District of Columbia" "Massachusetts" "New Jersey" ...
##  $ medianHouseholdIncome2021: int  90203 90088 89645 89296 88465 84907 84857 84247 83771 82254 ...

Once again this data must be cleaned because it has data for DC, Alaska and Hawaii, and the columns need to be renamed to allow for it to be made into a map.

#Removes Alaska, Hawaii, and DC
med_income <- subset(med_income, state != "Alaska")
med_income <- subset(med_income, state != "Hawaii")
med_income <- subset(med_income, state != "District of Columbia")

# Renaming the columns for easier usage
colnames(med_income) <- c("region","income")

# Making all state names lower case
med_income$region <- tolower(med_income$region)
str(med_income)
## 'data.frame':    48 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ region: chr  "maryland" "massachusetts" "new jersey" "new hampshire" ...
##  $ income: int  90203 89645 89296 88465 84907 84247 83771 82254 80963 79449 ...

Now that the data has been cleaned, we can use it to create a map and compare it to. First, here is the map seeing the percentage of people that would spend 4K to save their dog.

# Joining data set with state map
state_map <- map_data("state")
state_map_pets <- left_join(state_map,pet_data, by = "region")

# Graph for the percentage of people that would pay 4k to save their dog
pay4kGraph <- ggplot(state_map_pets, aes(x= long, y = lat, group = group)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(fill = spend4kPerc)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "turbo")
pay4kGraph

Next well plot the median income per state

# Joining data set with state map
state_map_med <- left_join(state_map,med_income, by = "region")

# Graph for the percentage of people that would pay 4k to save their dog
medGraph <- ggplot(state_map_med, aes(x= long, y = lat, group = group)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(fill = income)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "turbo")
medGraph

There is some correlation between the two maps. States with higher incomes such as California, Massachusetts, and New Jersey also have higher percentages of people that would spend $4K to save their dogs. Similarly, states with lower income like New Mexico, Arkansas, and Oklahoma were less likely to save their dog for $4K. This suggests that there is a correlation between median incomes and peoples willingness/ability to spend $4K to save their dog.

General Conclusion

1. Our pet ownership statistics data set had enough data to accurately answer all of our questions.

  1. A better way to answer these questions may involve making multiple graphs and comparing their complexities, going more in depth.

  2. Based on our findings, we would recommend decision makers to be aware of these statistics and what they mean for people and their pets. We found peoples dog devotion scores did not appear to correlate with whether or not they stayed at a job they disliked or were willing to spend $4k to save their dog. While people may have high devotion and care for their pets, it doesnt mean they have the means to, or are willing to spend up to $4k on them or stay at a disliked job. With this, we can recommend decision makers to look more into pet ownership expenses, either before getting their pet or why the bills are costing so much in the first place. An important aspect to also take into consideration when making a decision involving the data would be the preference of the type of pets that exist among people. After the analysis of our first and second questions we see a strong preference for dogs over cats; which is important to consider when we look at how much devotion exists for dogs when compared to other pets in the country.

  3. As stated above, there was a correlation between states incomes and their willingness to pay $4K to save their dog. This indicates that there is a corelation between the two. This indicates that even if a dog owner is very devoted to their dog, they may not be fincanically stable enough to make such a large payment, even if they wanted to.
